From eee085f4ab99883fd8d628bcebcc7d03762cf4b8 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Philippe Guibert <philippe.guibert@6wind.com>
Date: Thu, 26 Jun 2025 15:29:46 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 06/14] bgpd: add support to export both SRv6 and MPLS VPN
 prefixes

When a path is exported with a VPN prefix, configured with both MPLS and
SRv6, then both SRv6 and MPLS options are written in the same VPN prefix.
The MPLS label is overwritten.

> router bgp 1
>  segment-routing srv6
>   locator loc2
>  !
> !
> > router bgp 1 vrf vrf30
>  bgp router-id 192.0.2.1
>  no bgp ebgp-requires-policy
>  no bgp default ipv4-unicast
>  !
>  address-family ipv6 unicast
>   redistribute connected
>   label vpn export auto
>   sid vpn export auto
>   rd vpn export 1:30
>   rt vpn both 55:55
>   export vpn
>   import vpn
>  exit-address-family
> exit
>
> r1# show bgp ipv6 vpn
> [..]
> Route Distinguisher: 1:30
> *>  2001:8::/64      ::@9<                    0         32768 ?
>    UN=:: EC{55:55} label=64 sid=2002:db8:1:1:: sid_structure=[40,24,16,0] type=bgp, subtype=5
> r1# do show mpls table
>  Inbound Label  Type  Nexthop  Outbound Label
>  ----------------------------------------------
>  16             BGP   vrf30    -

To ease migration from MPLS to SRv6, VPN paths should be exportable with
the two options, to permit legacy and srv6-based devices to access to
that same prefix.

When both MPLS and SRv6 are present, export a specific VPN prefix for
each config. The third case where a VPN prefix is created with the
implicit-null value (for 'import vrf' command) is maintained.

Signed-off-by: Philippe Guibert <philippe.guibert@6wind.com>
